        <!-- Where the weight goes -->
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Where Does the Weight Go?</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.8125rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin-bottom:1rem;">Approximate distribution at full term</p>
          <div class="breakdown-grid" id="breakdownGrid">
            <div class="breakdown-item"><div class="breakdown-icon">&#x1F476;</div><div class="breakdown-label">Baby</div><div class="breakdown-value">7.5 lbs</div></div>
            <div class="breakdown-item"><div class="breakdown-icon">&#x1FA78;</div><div class="breakdown-label">Placenta</div><div class="breakdown-value">1.5 lbs</div></div>
            <div class="breakdown-item"><div class="breakdown-icon">&#x1F4A7;</div><div class="breakdown-label">Amniotic Fluid</div><div class="breakdown-value">2 lbs</div></div>
            <div class="breakdown-item"><div class="breakdown-icon">&#x1FA78;</div><div class="breakdown-label">Blood Volume</div><div class="breakdown-value">4 lbs</div></div>
            <div class="breakdown-item"><div class="breakdown-icon">&#x1F3E0;</div><div class="breakdown-label">Uterus Growth</div><div class="breakdown-value">2 lbs</div></div>
            <div class="breakdown-item"><div class="breakdown-icon">&#x1F930;</div><div class="breakdown-label">Breast Tissue</div><div class="breakdown-value">2 lbs</div></div>
            <div class="breakdown-item"><div class="breakdown-icon">&#x1F4A7;</div><div class="breakdown-label">Extra Fluids</div><div class="breakdown-value">4 lbs</div></div>
            <div class="breakdown-item"><div class="breakdown-icon">&#x26A1;</div><div class="breakdown-label">Fat Stores</div><div class="breakdown-value">7 lbs</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Week-by-week milestones -->
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Week-by-Week Weight Gain Milestones</h3>
          <div style="overflow-x:auto;">
            <table class="milestone-table" id="milestoneTable">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Week</th>
                  <th>Expected Gain (low)</th>
                  <th>Expected Gain (high)</th>
                  <th>Trimester</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody id="milestoneBody"></tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Trimester tips -->
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Tips by Trimester</h3>

          <div class="tri-section t1">
            <div class="tri-title">First Trimester (Weeks 1–12)</div>
            <div class="tri-weeks">Expected gain: 1–4.5 lbs</div>
            <ul class="tri-list">
              <li>Focus on nutrient-dense foods even if portions are small</li>
              <li>Take prenatal vitamins with folic acid daily</li>
              <li>Eat small, frequent meals to manage nausea</li>
              <li>Stay hydrated — aim for 8–10 glasses of water daily</li>
              <li>Don't worry about slight weight loss from morning sickness</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="tri-section t2">
            <div class="tri-title">Second Trimester (Weeks 13–27)</div>
            <div class="tri-weeks">Expected gain: ~1 lb/week</div>
            <ul class="tri-list">
              <li>Increase calorie intake by about 340 calories/day</li>
              <li>Prioritize protein, calcium, and iron-rich foods</li>
              <li>Continue regular physical activity (walking, swimming, prenatal yoga)</li>
              <li>Steady weight gain is more important than hitting exact targets</li>
              <li>Monitor weight weekly but avoid daily weigh-ins</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="tri-section t3">
            <div class="tri-title">Third Trimester (Weeks 28–40)</div>
            <div class="tri-weeks">Expected gain: ~1 lb/week</div>
            <ul class="tri-list">
              <li>Increase calorie intake by about 450 calories/day</li>
              <li>Focus on omega-3s (DHA) for baby's brain development</li>
              <li>Weight gain may slow or plateau in the final 1–2 weeks</li>
              <li>Eat fiber-rich foods to help with digestion</li>
              <li>Rest when needed — your body is working hard</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Medical disclaimer -->
        <div class="disclaimer">
          <div class="disclaimer-title">Medical Disclaimer</div>
          <p>This calculator provides general estimates based on IOM (Institute of Medicine) guidelines. Every pregnancy is unique. Weight gain recommendations may differ based on your individual health conditions, age, and medical history. Always consult your healthcare provider for personalized guidance about weight gain during pregnancy. This tool is not a substitute for professional medical advice.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SEO Content -->
      <div class="seo-content">
        <h2>How Much Weight Should You Gain During Pregnancy?</h2>
        <p>Gaining the right amount of weight during pregnancy is important for both your health and your baby's development. The Institute of Medicine (IOM) publishes evidence-based guidelines that recommend different weight gain ranges based on your pre-pregnancy Body Mass Index (BMI).</p>

        <h3>IOM Weight Gain Guidelines (Singleton Pregnancy)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Underweight (BMI &lt; 18.5):</strong> 28–40 pounds (12.5–18 kg)</li>
          <li><strong>Normal weight (BMI 18.5–24.9):</strong> 25–35 pounds (11.5–16 kg)</li>
          <li><strong>Overweight (BMI 25–29.9):</strong> 15–25 pounds (7–11.5 kg)</li>
          <li><strong>Obese (BMI ≥ 30):</strong> 11–20 pounds (5–9 kg)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Weight Gain for Twin Pregnancies</h3>
        <p>If you're carrying twins, the recommended weight gain is higher to support two growing babies:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Normal weight:</strong> 37–54 pounds</li>
          <li><strong>Overweight:</strong> 31–50 pounds</li>
          <li><strong>Obese:</strong> 25–42 pounds</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Understanding Pregnancy Weight Distribution</h3>
        <p>A common question is "where does all the weight go?" At full term, a typical 30-pound weight gain breaks down approximately as follows: the baby accounts for about 7.5 pounds, the placenta about 1.5 pounds, amniotic fluid about 2 pounds, increased blood volume about 4 pounds, extra body fluids about 4 pounds, uterus growth about 2 pounds, breast tissue about 2 pounds, and maternal fat stores about 7 pounds.</p>

        <h3>Week-by-Week Weight Gain Pattern</h3>
        <p>Weight gain during pregnancy is not evenly distributed across all 40 weeks. During the first trimester, most women gain only 1 to 4.5 pounds total. The majority of weight gain happens during the second and third trimesters, at a rate of approximately 1 pound per week for normal-weight women. The rate varies by BMI category — overweight women may gain about 0.5 to 0.7 pounds per week, while underweight women may gain slightly more.</p>

        <h3>Tips for Healthy Weight Gain</h3>
        <p>Focus on the quality of your diet rather than the quantity. Choose nutrient-dense foods like fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and dairy. Avoid "eating for two" — you only need about 340 extra calories per day in the second trimester and 450 in the third. Regular physical activity, such as walking or swimming, can help manage weight gain and improve overall pregnancy outcomes.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">How much weight should I gain during pregnancy?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">The recommended weight gain depends on your pre-pregnancy BMI. Underweight women (BMI &lt; 18.5) should gain 28–40 lbs, normal weight (BMI 18.5–24.9) should gain 25–35 lbs, overweight (BMI 25–29.9) should gain 15–25 lbs, and obese women (BMI ≥ 30) should gain 11–20 lbs. For twins, the recommendations are higher.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">How is pregnancy weight gain distributed in the body?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">A typical 30-pound pregnancy weight gain is distributed as: baby 7.5 lbs, placenta 1.5 lbs, amniotic fluid 2 lbs, uterus growth 2 lbs, breast tissue 2 lbs, increased blood volume 4 lbs, extra body fluids 4 lbs, and maternal fat stores 7 lbs.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">When do you gain the most weight during pregnancy?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Most weight gain occurs during the second and third trimesters. In the first trimester, you typically gain only 1–4.5 lbs total. During the second and third trimesters, you gain roughly 1 pound per week for normal-weight women, though the rate varies by BMI category.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Is it normal to lose weight in the first trimester?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes, slight weight loss in the first trimester is common due to morning sickness and nausea. Most women gain only 1–4.5 lbs in the first 12 weeks. If you lose more than 5% of your pre-pregnancy weight, consult your healthcare provider.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">How much weight should I gain with twins?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">For twin pregnancies, recommended weight gain is higher: normal weight women should gain 37–54 lbs, overweight women 31–50 lbs, and obese women 25–42 lbs. Your healthcare provider will help you determine the right target based on your individual situation.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">What happens if I gain too much or too little weight?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Gaining too little weight increases the risk of preterm birth and low birth weight. Gaining too much weight increases the risk of gestational diabetes, high blood pressure, C-section delivery, and postpartum weight retention. Both extremes can be managed with guidance from your healthcare provider.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">How does BMI affect pregnancy weight gain recommendations?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">The Institute of Medicine (IOM) bases pregnancy weight gain guidelines on pre-pregnancy BMI. Women who start pregnancy underweight are advised to gain more (28–40 lbs) to support healthy fetal growth, while women who start overweight or obese are advised to gain less (11–25 lbs) to reduce complications.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Can I diet during pregnancy to control weight gain?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Restrictive dieting during pregnancy is not recommended as it can deprive your baby of essential nutrients. Instead, focus on nutrient-dense foods, appropriate portion sizes, and regular physical activity approved by your healthcare provider. If you're concerned about weight gain, talk to your doctor or a registered dietitian.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

